Package uri

Interface Uri

  • public interface Uri
    Represents a fully encoded URI for a subset and variant of RFC 3986.

    The following grammar defines the URIs represented by this class and parsed by UriParser. Each rule is of the form non-terminal = expression. Expressions are constructed with:

    • literals enclosed by " quotation marks.
    • alternatives separated by slashes (/).
      The leftmost has highest priority and the rightmost alternative the least.
    • groups enclosed by parentheses.
    • optional groups enclosed by square brackets ([]).
    • literal ranges such as "0"-"4", which is equivalent to ("0"/"1"/"2"/"3"/"4").
    • 0 or more repetitions of an expression marked by an asterisk *.

    Semicolons (;) indicate a comment for the rest of the line. See wikipedia (German) or wikipedia (English) for more explanation. Note that we use "a"-"z" and "0"-"9" and similar ranges here, which are not an official part of the ABNF RFC, but their meaning remains clear. 

     
 URI           = scheme ":" hierarchical [ "?" query ]

 hierarchical  = "//" authority path

 scheme        = ALPHA *( ALPHA / DIGIT )

 authority     = [ userinfo "@" ] host
 userinfo      = *( pchar / ":" )
 host          = IPv4address / reg-name

 IPv4address   = dec-octet "." dec-octet "." dec-octet "." dec-octet

 dec-octet     = ["0" ["0"]] DIGIT      ; 000-009 with optional leading zeros
               / ["0"] "1"-"9" DIGIT    ; 010-099
               / "1" DIGIT DIGIT        ; 100-199
               / "2" "0"-"4" DIGIT      ; 200-249
               / "25" "0"-"5"           ; 250-255

 reg-name      = *pchar

 path          = *( "/" *pchar )        ; begins with "/" or is empty

 query         = *( pchar / "&" / "=" )

 pchar         = unreserved / pct-encoded
 unreserved    = ALPHA / DIGIT / "."
 pct-encoded   = "%" HEXDIGIT HEXDIGIT

 ALPHA         = "A"-"Z" / "a"-"z"
 DIGIT         = "0"-"9"
 HEXDIGIT      = DIGIT / "A"-"F" / "a"-"f"
    This interface will be overwritten with the original version when testing.
